  skos:definition "Isotope dilution is a technique for the determination of elemental concentrations in minerals, rocks, and fluids. This technique involves the addition of an exactly known amount of an enriched isotope (or sometimes two or three enriched isotopes) “spike” or “tracer” to the sample material. The resulting isotopic composition of the sample-spike mixture with the known amount of spike, and the weight of the sample the elemental concentration of the original sample can be readily determined to an ultra-trace level (i.e. sub pg g-1)."@en ;
  skos:inScheme <https://w3id.org/geochem/1.1/analyticalmethod/method> ;
  skos:narrower <https://w3id.org/geochem/1.0/TESTanalyticaltechnique/technique/chemical-abrasion-isotope-dilution-thermal-ionisation-mass-spectrometry> ;
  skos:narrower <https://w3id.org/geochem/1.0/TESTanalyticaltechnique/technique/isotope-dilution-negative-ion-thermal-ionisation-mass-spectrometry> ;
  skos:narrower <https://w3id.org/geochem/1.0/TESTanalyticaltechnique/technique/isotope-dilution-positive-ion-thermal-ionisation-mass-spectrometry> ;
  skos:notation "ID-TI-MS" ;
  skos:prefLabel "Isotope dilution thermal ionisation mass spectrometry"@en ;
.
